    The error "Deallocation of non-allocated memory" occurs because the         
    program is attempting to delete a pointer (n) that does not point to the    
    beginning of the memory block allocated by new.                             
                                                                                
    Analysis                                                                    
                                                                                
    Looking at the source code in program.cpp:                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     9    int * n = new int(100);                                               
     10   n--;                  // Subtracts from the pointer                   
     11   delete n;             // Attempts to delete the modified pointer      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     1 Line 9: int * n = new int(100); allocates memory on the heap for an      
       integer. The pointer n holds the address of this allocated memory.       
     2 Line 10: n--; decrements the address stored in the pointer. If the       
       integer at that heap location is at address 0xABC, n now points to       
       0xABC - sizeof(int) (e.g., 0xA98).                                       
     3 Line 11: delete n; is called. The C++ delete operator expects a pointer  
       that was returned by new. Since n was decremented and no longer points   
       to the start of the buffer new allocated, the memory management system   
       detects that an invalid address is being deallocated, triggering the     
       "Deallocation of non-allocated memory" error (frequently raised by       
       memory sanitizers like ASan).                                            
                                                                                
    Root Cause                                                                  
                                                                                
    The root cause is manual pointer arithmetic on a heap-allocated pointer     
    before passing it to delete. This violates the contract of the delete       
    operator, which requires the exact pointer returned by new.                 
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendations                                                             
                                                                                
    Minimal Fix                                                                 
                                                                                
    Remove the incorrect pointer arithmetic on line 10.                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     9    int * n = new int(100);                                               
     10   // n--; Remove or fix this decrement                                  
     11   delete n;                                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Thorough Root-Cause Fix                                                     
                                                                                
    Avoid manual memory management wherever possible. Use std::unique_ptr or    
    std::shared_ptr from the <memory> header, which automatically manage the    
    memory lifecycle and eliminate the possibility of calling delete on an      
    incorrect or invalidated pointer.                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <memory>                                                          
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
       auto n = std::make_unique<int>(100);                                     
       // ... no need to call delete manually, and no risk of invalidating      
     the pointer                                                                
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
